Size and Orientation: Match effects across three langauges

Sau-Chin Chen

2017-01-18

Authors

Sau-Chin Chen, Bjorn de Koning, Rolf Zwaan, and Yu-Han Luo

Hypothesis

In our pre-registered proposal: “Match effects of object orientation in the sentence-picture verification task are consistently smaller than object shape, color, and size. We hypothesize that this may be due to the fact that the orientation objects are small and manipulable. This study asks the questions if object size constrains object orientation effects, such that effects for smaller, manipulable, items are smaller than for larger, nonmanipulable objects. A pilot study yielded larger match effects for the large objects than for the small objects both in English and in Dutch speakers. In addition, a Bayesian analysis indicated that the stronger match effect occurred for the horizontal objects of English participants and the stronger match effect happened to the vertical objects of Dutch participants. The pre-registered experiment will update the design of sentence-picture verification based on our pilots and test the hypotheses in advance. A third language, Chinese, will be included to test the stronger match effect for the large objects than the small objects and to confirm the inconsistent match effects across horizontal and vertical objects. Alternative recognition trials will be triggered after each eight trials. These recognition trials are used to make sure the participants have paid their attentions on the probe sentences. Meta-analyses will be performed on the data for the three experiments. We expect that effects generalize across languages and therefore that language will not be a signficant moderator of the observed effects.”

Method

Participants

The participants came from three langauge backgrounds: English(the United States), Dutch(EUR students), Chinese(Taiwan undergraduates). 150 English participants were the US residents who were recruited from Amazon Mechanical Turk. Every English participant finished the experiment in Qualtrics platform and obtained US$ 1.5 dollars as the reward. Total 128 valid participants’ data (91 females; averaged age is 44.15 and the range is 20 - 74) are collected after excluded the participants who met the accidental stop and considered the equal numbers between the stimuli lists.
The undergraudates in EUR and NCKU participated in the Dutch and Chinese versions in the laboratories of EUR EBL and NCKU LACD Lab. They obtained the course credits or US$ 2-3 dollars as the reward. 64 Taiwan students (44 females; averaged age is 20 and the range is 18 - 22) joined the Chinese version. So far, 54 Dutch students (41 females; averaged age is 21 and the range is 18 - 24) joined the Dutch version.

Stimuli and Design

64 sets of critical stimuli are decided by the language backgrounds (English, Dutch, and Chinese), the object size (Large, Small), the object orientation (Horizontal, Verticl), and the matching the probe sentence and target picture(match, mismatch). Half of the sets represent the large objects, and the other half represent the small objects. In each set two pictures show the target object in horizontal and in vertical respectively. The format of target pictures are the grey scaled jpeg files in 240 X 240 pixels. Each picture matches one of the probe sentence whereas mismatches the other probe sentence. Every probe sentence are written in English, Dutch, and Chinese for the participants in the respective langauge backgrounds. The objects are the initial nouns of the probe sentences. We used this sentence strucure according to our earlier pilot study.

Examples of large objects
Matched Picture Mismatched Picture
The canoe was gliding across the river.
The canoe was dropping from the top of the water fall.
Examples of small objects
Matched Picture Mismatched Picture
The hat was on the model’s head.
The hat hung on the wall.

64 filler pairs of sentences and pictures are decided for the demand of verification task. In each pair the picture are irrelavent to the sentence. The sentence strucure and the picture format are identical to the critical stimuli.

Procedure

The experimental session began after 6 practice trials. Each practice trial is the sentence-picture verification task as identical to the settings of Stanfield and Zwaan(2001) and Zwaan and Pechers (2012). Because the limitations of experimental software, the English participants finished the 6 practices trials with feedback, but the Dutch and Chinese participants finished the pratice session till they correctly answered all the 6 practice trials.

The experimental session had 128 trials of sentence-picture verifiaction task and 30 to 32 trials of the alternative task. For the English participants, the alternative task is the comprehension task follows the settings of Zwaan and Pechers (2012). 32 multiple choices present after 32 fillers. These trials require the participants answer the questions about the probe sentences they just read. For the Dutch and Chinese participants, the alternative task is recognition task as like Stanfield and Zwaan (2001). 30 yes/no problems present randomly between the 128 experimental trials. These problems require the participant recognize if the sentence just shown in the recent three trials or not.

In addition to the main effect of object size, F(1,189) = 294.96, MSE = 6139.29, p = 0, the main effects of the other three independent variables do not reach the statistical significant level (p > .05). Between the two-way interactions, only the interaction of object size and match effects was beyond the statistical significant level, F(1,189) = 6.2, MSE = 4734.45, p = 0.014. Between the three-way interactions, only the interaction of object size, orientation, and match effects was beyond the statistical significant level, F(1,189) = 4.51, MSE = 5847.88, p = 0.035. Participants’ response times obviously increased with the object size, and the patterns of match effects were different between the object size. The object orientation moderated the match effects between the object size. There are no significant differences of participants’ responses among the three languages.

Brief discussion on the analysis of accuracy The ANOVA for the accuracy as the dependent variable indicated the Chinese participants made more incorrect responses than the other two groups. The main effect of match effects is significant because of the averaged accuracy of Chinese participants. The interaction of language groups and size shows the effect of object size increasing with the sample size.

Primay analysis: Meta-analysis

In the pre-registered proposal: “A meta-analytic effect size of the match effects across languages, size, and orientation will be summarized. This meta-analysis will confirm that the match effects could shift with the object size and orientations but have a stable pattern across languages.”

In the meta analysis #1, I calcuated the effect size of each condition based on participants’ median RT and standardize deviation. The confidence intervals represent the match effect estimated by the difference of medians.

require(metafor)
## Create data set for escalc()
dat_3IV = data.frame(
condition = unique(with(data = DATA_3IV, paste(Lang, Size, Orientation))),
m_match = as.vector( with(data = subset(DATA_3IV, Match == "Y"), tapply(RT, paste(Lang,Size,Orientation),median) ) ),
m_mismatch = as.vector( with(data = subset(DATA_3IV, Match == "N"), tapply(RT, paste(Lang,Size,Orientation),median) ) ),
sd_match = as.vector( with(data = subset(DATA_3IV, Match == "Y"), tapply(RT, paste(Lang,Size,Orientation),sd) ) ),
sd_mismatch = as.vector( with(data = subset(DATA_3IV, Match == "N"), tapply(RT, paste(Lang,Size,Orientation),sd) ) ),
ni = as.vector( with(data = subset(DATA_3IV, Match == "Y"), tapply(ID, paste(Lang,Size,Orientation), length) ) ),
ri = rep(.5,12)
)
## Calculate effect size of 12 conditions
dat_3IV_es <- escalc(measure = "MC", m1i = m_mismatch, m2i = m_match, sd1i = sd_mismatch, sd2i = sd_match, ni = ni, ri = ri, slab = condition, data = dat_3IV)
## Do the meta analysis on 12 conditions, in random effect model
dat_3IV_meta <- rma.uni(yi, vi, data = dat_3IV_es, slab = condition, method = "REML", digits = 2)
## Draw the main forest plot for all conditions and overall meta-analytical effect
forest(dat_3IV_meta, cex = .65, ylim = c(-1, 21), order = c(1,5,9,2,6,10,3,7,11,4,8,12), rows = c(12:14,16:18,3:5,7:9), xlab = "Effect size of match effects", mlab = "RE model for all conditions")
## Do the meta analysis on the large and vertical objects, in random effect model
dat_3IV_large_V_meta <- rma.uni(yi, vi, data = dat_3IV_es[c(2,6,10),], slab = condition, method = "REML", digits = 2)
## Do the meta analysis on the large and horizontal objects, in random effect model
dat_3IV_large_H_meta <- rma.uni(yi, vi, data = dat_3IV_es[c(1,5,9),], slab = condition, method = "REML", digits = 2)
## Do the meta analysis on the large objects, in random effect model
dat_3IV_large_meta <- rma.uni(yi, vi, data = dat_3IV_es[c(1,2,5,6,9,10),], slab = condition, method = "REML", digits = 2)
## Do the meta analysis on the small vertical objects, in random effect model
dat_3IV_small_V_meta <- rma.uni(yi, vi, data = dat_3IV_es[c(4,8,12),], slab = condition, method = "REML", digits = 2)
## Do the meta analysis on the small horizontal objects, in random effect model
dat_3IV_small_H_meta <- rma.uni(yi, vi, data = dat_3IV_es[c(3,7,11),], slab = condition, method = "REML", digits = 2)
## Do the meta analysis on the small objects, in random effect model
dat_3IV_small_meta <- rma.uni(yi, vi, data = dat_3IV_es[c(3,4,7,8,11,12),], slab = condition, method = "REML", digits = 2)
## Draw the meta-analytical effect of large objects on the main forest plot
addpoly(dat_3IV_large_V_meta, row = 15, cex = .65, mlab = "RE model for large and vertical objects")
addpoly(dat_3IV_large_H_meta, row = 11, cex = .65, mlab = "RE model for large and horizontal objects")
addpoly(dat_3IV_large_meta, row = 10, cex = .65, mlab = "RE model for large objects")
## Draw the meta-analytical effect of small objects on the main forest plot
addpoly(dat_3IV_small_V_meta, row = 6, cex = .65, mlab = "RE model for small and vertical objects")
addpoly(dat_3IV_small_H_meta, row = 2, cex = .65, mlab = "RE model for small and horizontal objects")
addpoly(dat_3IV_small_meta, row = 1, cex = .65, mlab = "RE model for small objects")

In the meta analysis #2, I calcuated the by-participant effect size for each condition. The by-pariticipant effect sizes are estimated by the pooling variance for each participant. This method needs some expert help verification.

## Create data set by participant and condition for escalc()
dat_subj_3IV = data.frame(
        subset(DATA_3IV, Match == "Y"),
        subset(DATA_3IV, Match == "N")[,c(7,8,9)]
)[,c(1:8,11,12,9,13,10)]
names(dat_subj_3IV) <- c("Lang","List","ID","Size","Orientation","Match","Match_RT","Match_RTsd","Mismatch_RT","Mismatch_RTsd","Match_ACC","Mismatch_ACC","MEM_ACC")
# Every participant contributed 8 trials to each condition.
dat_subj_3IV = data.frame(dat_subj_3IV, ni = rep(8, dim(dat_subj_3IV)[1]), ri = rep(.5,dim(dat_subj_3IV)[1]))

## Meta-anlysis of null model
dat_subj_3IV_es <- escalc(measure = "MC", m1i = Mismatch_RT, m2i = Match_RT, sd1i = Mismatch_RTsd, sd2i = Match_RTsd, ni = ni, ri = ri, slab = paste(Lang, ID, Size, Orientation), data = dat_subj_3IV)
## Make sure the random variations are in the reasonable range
dat_subj_3IV_null_model <- rma(yi = yi, sei = sqrt(vi), method = "ML", data = dat_subj_3IV_es)
funnel(dat_subj_3IV_null_model, xlab = "by-participant match effects", pch = levels(dat_subj_3IV_es$Lang))

## Meta-analysis with participants' variation as moderator
dat_subj_3IV_subj_error <- rma(yi = yi, sei = sqrt(vi), mods = ~ sqrt(vi), method = "ML", data = dat_subj_3IV_es)
## Meta-analysis with all independent variables as moderator
dat_subj_3IV_Lang <- rma(yi = yi, sei = sqrt(vi), mods = ~ sqrt(vi) + Lang, method = "ML", data = dat_subj_3IV_es)
dat_subj_3IV_Size <- rma(yi = yi, sei = sqrt(vi), mods = ~ sqrt(vi) + Size, method = "ML", data = dat_subj_3IV_es)
dat_subj_3IV_Orientation <- rma(yi = yi, sei = sqrt(vi), mods = ~ sqrt(vi) + Orientation, method = "ML", data = dat_subj_3IV_es)
dat_subj_3IV_LangxSize <- rma(yi = yi, sei = sqrt(vi), mods = ~ sqrt(vi) + Lang * Size, method = "ML", data = dat_subj_3IV_es)
dat_subj_3IV_LangxOrientation <- rma(yi = yi, sei = sqrt(vi), mods = ~ sqrt(vi) + Lang * Orientation, method = "ML", data = dat_subj_3IV_es)
dat_subj_3IV_SizexOrientation <- rma(yi = yi, sei = sqrt(vi), mods = ~ sqrt(vi) + Size * Orientation, method = "ML", data = dat_subj_3IV_es)
dat_subj_3IV_3way <- rma(yi = yi, sei = sqrt(vi), mods = ~ sqrt(vi) + Lang * Size * Orientation, method = "ML", data = dat_subj_3IV_es)
## Comparisons with the base line model
aov01 <- anova(dat_subj_3IV_subj_error, dat_subj_3IV_Lang)
aov02 <- anova(dat_subj_3IV_subj_error, dat_subj_3IV_Size)
aov03 <- anova(dat_subj_3IV_subj_error, dat_subj_3IV_Orientation)
aov04 <-  anova(dat_subj_3IV_subj_error, dat_subj_3IV_LangxSize)
aov05 <-  anova(dat_subj_3IV_subj_error, dat_subj_3IV_LangxOrientation)
aov06 <-  anova(dat_subj_3IV_subj_error, dat_subj_3IV_SizexOrientation)
aov07 <- anova(dat_subj_3IV_subj_error, dat_subj_3IV_3way)

As like the multiple regression analysis, all the models that possibly fitted the data are exclusively computed. Here are the comparisons with the baseline model(Y = se(i)).

BFplus0 represents how much the current evidence favor the alternative hypothesis against the null hypothesis. A BFplus0 which is larger than ten represents the strong evidence. A BFplus0 which is smaller than 1 represents the null evidence.

When the prior is 0.707, Bayes factors show the strong evidence for the large and vertical objects from the English participants. The evidences from the Dutch participants will settle down in the end of the evidence.

Discussion

  1. Large objects, especially vertical objects, tend to generate the match advantage across the three language groups. Small objects fail to cause the match effects, but there was a match disadvantage happened to the Taiwan participants.

  2. In the pilot study, English participants and Dutch participants tended to show the match advantages of the large objects and the match disadvantages of the small objects. The critical study shows the contribution of vertical objects to the match advantages of large objects, 20.55[4.91, 36.19], and the null effects of the small objects.

  3. Taiwan participants show the overall null effect of matching. In this data set, the meta analysis reveals the significant match disadvantage for the small and vertical objects, -28.66[-53.85, -3.87]. However, this data set does not cause the overall match disadvantage for the small and vertial objects, -10.50[-30.20, 9.19].

  4. Question 1: Have we to distinguish the horizontal and vertical orientations of large objects? If people easier simulated the visaul image of large objects than the small objects, they have the response advantage for the large objects presented in the typical orientation. This brings two testable hypotheses: (1) Large objects are easier simulated than small objects; (2) Large objects are easier simulated in the typical orientation. We may need to build the norm that classify the typtical orientation of the large objects.

  5. Question 2: Why do the Taiwan participants show the weaker match effects than the English and Dutch participants? Taiwanese started reading and writing in the vertical direction. Although many adult Taiwanese are used to vertical and horizontal orientation, they firstly learned the object shape with the text printed in the vertical direction. We may compare the match effects of small objects in the horizontal reading direction and in the vertical reading direction. If the vertical reading direction could help Taiwanese image the object shape, it could to find the significant match effect in the vertical direction rather than the horizontal direction. The replications of classical orientation studies (Stanfield and Zwaan ,2001; Zwaan and Pecher, 2012) could test this hypothesis.
